    <name>
      <text>17.1.1.6 Equations of circles</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[Find the centre and radius of each of the following circles:

<ol class="HELM_parts">
    <li><p>\({@poly1=0@}\)</p>
        <p>Centre: \((\)[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] ,[[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]]\()\)</p>
        <p>Radius: [[input:ans3]][[validation:ans3]]</p>
      <p>[[feedback:prt1]]</p>
    </li>

    <li><p>\({@poly2=0@}\)</p>
        <p>Centre: \((\)[[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]], [[input:ans5]] [[validation:ans5]]\()\)</p>
        <p>Radius: [[input:ans6]][[validation:ans6]]</p>
      <p>[[feedback:prt2]]</p></li>
</ol>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<ol type="a">
    <li>We observe that \({@at(poly1,y=0)-const1@} = {@(x-a1)^2 -expand((x-a1)^2 - (at(poly1,y=0)-const1) )@}\) and&nbsp;\({@at(poly1,x=0)-const1@} = {@(y-b1)^2 -expand((y-b1)^2 - (at(poly1,x=0)-const1) )@}\). Hence we may rearrange to obtain: \[{@poly1@}
        =&nbsp;{@(x-a1)^2 -expand((x-a1)^2 - (at(poly1,y=0)-const1) )+(y-b1)^2 -expand((y-b1)^2 - (at(poly1,x=0)-const1) )+ const1@}= 0 .\]
        <p>Hence the centre is \(({@c1[1]@},{@c1[2]@})\), and the radius is \(\sqrt{{@r1^2@}} = {@r1@}\).</p>
    </li>
    <li>First we divide through by \({@1/r2^2@}\) to obtain \({@poly2a@}=0\). We then observe that \({@at(poly2a,y=0)-const2@} = {@(x-a2)^2 -expand((x-a2)^2 - (at(poly2a,y=0)-const2) )@}\) and&nbsp;\({@at(poly2a,x=0)-const2@} = {@(y-b2)^2 -expand((y-b2)^2 - (at(poly2a,x=0)-const2) )@}\). Hence we may rearrange to obtain: \[{@poly2a@}
        =&nbsp;{@(x-a2)^2 -expand((x-a2)^2 - (at(poly2a,y=0)-const2) )+(y-b2)^2 -expand((y-b2)^2 - (at(poly2a,x=0)-const2) )+ const2@}= 0 .\]
        <p>Hence the centre is \(({@c2[1]@},{@c2[2]@})\), and the radius is \(\sqrt{{@r2^2@}} = {@r2@}\).</p>
    </li>
</ol>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
